# ElevenLabs Voice Agent

## When to Use

This integration is already set up and ready to use. Apply these patterns whenever a task mentions:

- **Voice agent**, voice assistant, voice bot, voice AI, conversational AI
- **ElevenLabs**, Eleven Labs, 11 Labs, 11labs
- **Voice data collection**, collect via voice, voice survey, voice intake, voice form
- **Real-time voice conversation**, talk to AI, speak to agent

When any of the above are mentioned, use the existing `useVoiceAgent()` hook and `lib/elevenlabs.ts` â€” do NOT install new packages or create new abstractions. The infrastructure is already wired in both `apps/web` and `apps/react-native`.

### Existing Files (already implemented)

**Web** (`apps/web`):
- `src/lib/elevenlabs.ts` â€” feature flag (`elevenlabsEnabled`) and `ELEVENLABS_AGENT_ID`
- `src/hooks/use-voice-agent.ts` â€” `useVoiceAgent()` hook
- `src/app/voice-agent/page.tsx` â€” demo page at `/voice-agent`

**React Native** (`apps/react-native`):
- `lib/elevenlabs.ts` â€” feature flag and agent ID
- `hooks/use-voice-agent.ts` â€” `useVoiceAgent()` hook
- `app/(tabs)/voice-agent.tsx` â€” demo screen
- `app/_layout.tsx` â€” `ElevenLabsWrapper` provider (already in root layout)

### Quick Start for New Features

To add a voice agent to a new page or screen, just import the hook:

```typescript
import { useVoiceAgent } from "@/hooks/use-voice-agent";

const { enabled, status, isSpeaking, messages, start, stop } = useVoiceAgent();
```

No provider setup needed on web. React Native is already wrapped with `ElevenLabsProvider` in the root layout.

## SDK Selection

- **Web**: Use `@elevenlabs/react` â€” provides the `useConversation` hook for WebRTC/WebSocket voice conversations in the browser. No additional native dependencies needed.
- **React Native**: Use `@elevenlabs/react-native` â€” provides `ElevenLabsProvider` and `useConversation` hook. Requires LiveKit peer dependencies (`@livekit/react-native`, `@livekit/react-native-webrtc`, `livekit-client`) for WebRTC on mobile. Expo Go is **not** supported â€” requires a development build.

## Environment Variables

Client-side only (public agent IDs):
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_ELEVENLABS_AGENT_ID` â€” web agent ID from ElevenLabs dashboard
- `EXPO_PUBLIC_ELEVENLABS_AGENT_ID` â€” React Native agent ID

Agent IDs are public and safe to expose. Create agents at https://elevenlabs.io/app/conversational-ai.

## Graceful Fallback

All ElevenLabs features must degrade gracefully when the agent ID env var is missing. Follow the same pattern as Stripe and Google Analytics.

- Export `elevenlabsEnabled` from `lib/elevenlabs.ts` â€” check before rendering any voice agent UI
- `useVoiceAgent()` returns `enabled: false` and no-op methods when not configured
- Voice agent pages/screens show a "not configured" message with setup instructions

## Wrapper Hook

Use `useVoiceAgent()` (in `hooks/use-voice-agent.ts` for both web and react-native) as the app-level wrapper:

```typescript
const { enabled, status, isSpeaking, messages, start, stop, sendFeedback } = useVoiceAgent();
```

This hook wraps the SDK's `useConversation` and adds:
- Graceful fallback when not configured
- Microphone permission management (web)
- Message history tracking
- Consistent interface across web and mobile

## Microphone Permissions

ElevenLabs requires microphone access for voice conversations.

- **Web**: Call `navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({ audio: true })` before starting a conversation. Handle the denied case with a user-friendly message.
- **React Native**: Configure `NSMicrophoneUsageDescription` in `Info.plist` (iOS) and `RECORD_AUDIO` permission in `AndroidManifest.xml` (Android). The SDK handles permission requests at runtime.

## Connection Types

- **WebRTC** (preferred): Lower latency, better audio quality. Default for React Native. Available on web via `connectionType: "webrtc"`.
- **WebSocket**: Fallback option for web when WebRTC is not available. Use `connectionType: "websocket"`.

## Provider Setup

### Web
No provider needed. The `useConversation` hook from `@elevenlabs/react` works standalone.

### React Native
Wrap the app with `ElevenLabsProvider` in the root layout. Use the conditional wrapper pattern:

```typescript
function ElevenLabsWrapper({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  if (!elevenlabsEnabled) return <>{children}</>;
  const { ElevenLabsProvider } = require("@elevenlabs/react-native");
  return <ElevenLabsProvider>{children}</ElevenLabsProvider>;
}
```

## Key SDK Methods

- `startSession({ agentId })` â€” start a conversation with a public agent
- `endSession()` â€” end the current conversation
- `sendFeedback(true/false)` â€” thumbs up/down on the latest agent response
- `sendUserMessage(text)` â€” send a text message instead of voice
- `sendContextualUpdate(text)` â€” inform the agent of context changes without triggering a response

## Rules

- **DO** check `elevenlabsEnabled` before rendering voice agent UI components
- **DO** request microphone permission with user-friendly UI before starting a conversation
- **DO** use `useVoiceAgent()` hook for consistent patterns across web and mobile
- **DO** handle all conversation states in UI (connecting, connected/listening, speaking, disconnected)
- **DO** show a "not configured" fallback when the agent ID env var is missing
- **DO** clean up conversations on component unmount (call `endSession`)
- **DO NOT** call `startSession()` without a valid agent ID
- **DO NOT** skip microphone permission checks â€” always request before connecting
- **DO NOT** hardcode agent IDs in components â€” use env vars via `lib/elevenlabs.ts`
- **DO NOT** import `@elevenlabs/react-native` unconditionally â€” use dynamic `require()` behind the `elevenlabsEnabled` check to avoid crashes when LiveKit native modules are not linked
